\chapter{Nuclear excitation by electron capture}
\label{chap:NEEC}


%------------------------------------------------------------------------------------%

Over the last decades the process of electron-ion recombination has been studied extensively in theory as well as in experiments. It is one of the fundamental atomic processes which plays an important role in many branches of physics. For instance, in semiconductor physics the carrier-hole recombination builds the basis for many semiconductor electronic devices like photodiodes, LEDs, transistors, solar cells to name a few. Or, in non-equilibrium plasmas the recombination is the main counterpart to ionization and excitation processes whose interplay determines the ionization balance and the atomic state populations. Moreover, electron-ion recombination followed by the emission of a photon gives one of the major contributions to the radiation field emitted by plasmas. In particular in plasmas that are not accessible by direct probes, the detection of the emitted light is the principal way to analyze the prevailing plasma conditions which again requires a good understanding of the recombination processes.

The case when the capture of the initially free electron into a bound state of the ion is followed by the emission of a photon is the so-called photo recombination (PR). The direct, non-resonant channel of PR is called radiative recombination (RR). In this process the electron recombination involves the emission of a photon ensuring energy and momentum conservation. The process of RR not only plays an important role in plasma physics as already pointed out above, but also takes the responsibility for the main background in ion trap or electron-ion collision experiments. RR has been the subject of many theoretical and experimental studies in a broad spectrum of fields of physics.

Instead of emitting a photon, the capture energy (the energy difference between the free electron and the bound state) can also be transferred to an initially bound electron by stimulating a bound-bound transition. This process is referred to as dielectronic recombination (DR) and when followed by radiative decay of the excited electronic state in a second step, provides an indirect, resonant contribution to PR. The interference between the RR and the DR channel has already been under investigation in Refs.~\cite{Shabaev1994, Zimmermann1997}. Moreover, DR is expected to give the dominant contribution to PR especially in hot astrophysical plasmas. Note that DR is a resonant process because the capture energy and the electronic transition energy need to match in order for the recombination to take place.

The nuclear analog to DR is nuclear excitation by electron capture, short NEEC. In the process of NEEC the initially free electron is captured into a bound state and simultaneously transfers its capture energy to the nucleus. In Fig.~\ref{fig:neec-process}, NEEC is illustrated for the example of an $L$-shell capture with a fully occupied $K$ shell (1s$^2$) followed by the radiative decay of the nuclear excited level. It is again important to note that the energy difference between the free and the bound electronic state needs to coincide with the nuclear transition energy in order for NEEC to take place (see middle part of Fig.~\ref{fig:neec-process}). Analogously to DR, the process of NEEC followed by radiative decay of the nucleus gives an additional channel to PR. The interference between NEEC followed by the emission of a photon and RR has been studied theoretically in Ref.~\cite{Adriana2007.PRA-interference}.

\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics[width=1.0\linewidth]{pics/neec-process-3.pdf}
\caption{NEEC followed by radiative decay. An initially free electron is captured by a He-like ion into the $L$ shell. This capture energy is simultaneously transfered to the nucleus which is driven into an excited state. The created resonant state subsequently decays back to the nuclear ground state by emitting a photon.}
\label{fig:neec-process}
\end{figure}

The process of NEEC has been first proposed theoretically by Goldanskii and Namiot in 1976 \cite{Goldanskii1976-NEEC}. Since then NEEC has been subject to a number of theoretical studies in plasma environments \cite{Harston1999.PRC, Gosselin2004.PRC, Gosselin2007.PRC, Gosselin2010.PRC, Morel2010.PRC} as well as in solid targets \cite{Cue1989.epl, Cue1989, Kimball1991, Yuan1993}. Although there have been efforts to verify the existence of NEEC experimentally, no NEEC signal has been measured yet. The main obstacle seems to be the large background created by RR \cite{gsi89, thesis-Dauvergne}. In contrast, the time reversed process of NEEC called internal conversion (IC) where the nuclear de-excitation kicks out a bound electron, is a well established nuclear decay mechanism. Moreover, related processes like nuclear excitation by electron transition (NEET) \cite{Kishimoto2000-NEET} and its time reversal, bound internal conversion (BIC) \cite{Carreyre2000-BIC}, have already been demonstrated in experiments. In the process of NEET the nuclear excitation is driven by a bound-bound electronic transition instead of free-bound like in the case of NEEC. Based on these achievements, there is no disbelief that the process of NEEC exists and it may be only a question of overcoming the large RR background until the first NEEC signal is detected.

This Chapter is devoted to the theoretical treatment of NEEC which follows the approach developed by P\'{a}lffy \cite{thesis-Ada, Adriana2006.PRA}. In order to derive the cross section for NEEC followed by radiative decay of the nucleus, P\'{a}lffy uses a perturbation expansion of the transition operator analogously as it has been done for RR and DR \cite{Zimmerer1990, thesis-Zimmerer}. Moreover, a Feshbach projection operator method is applied \cite{Haan1989, Zimmermann1997} which allows to separate the subspaces of initial, intermediate and final states. In Ref.~\cite{Adriana2006.PRA}, the capture into bare nuclei or He-like ions has been considered which makes it possible to reduce the electronic part into a one-electron problem. Here, we extend the formalism to many electron wave functions analogously to how it has been performed for NEET in Ref.~\cite{Agrigapudi2012.PRA}. However, we do not go into the details of the perturbation expansion or of the projection method which have been given elsewhere \cite{thesis-Ada, Adriana2006.PRA}.

In Sec.~\ref{sec:decomposition}, we first discuss the decomposition of the Fock space into initial, intermediate and final states as illustrated in Fig.~\ref{fig:neec-process}. In Sec.~\ref{sec:Hamiltonian} the Hamilton operator of the system is introduced. Moreover, we sketch the nuclear model used for describing the nuclear degrees of freedom. Sec.~\ref{sec:sigma-NEEC} is solely devoted to the derivation of the total NEEC cross section. Explicit formulas for the electric and magnetic NEEC rates in terms of reduced transition probabilities and electronic wave functions are derived in Sec.~\ref{sec:Y-NEEC}. Atomic units $\hbar=m_{\rm{e}}=e=4\pi\varepsilon_0=1$ are employed throughout this Chapter.



%------------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\section{Decomposition of Fock space}
\label{sec:decomposition}

The initial state of the system consists of the nucleus in its ground state, an electronic configuration with a free electron and the radiation field in the vacuum state. The composed state vector can be written as a direct product of nuclear, electronic and photonic degrees of freedom,
%
\begin{equation}\label{eq:psi_i}
| \Psi_{\rm{i}} \rangle = | I_{\rm{i}}M_{\rm{i}}, \Psi_{\rm{i}}^{\rm{el}} , 0 \rangle \equiv
| I_{\rm{i}}M_{\rm{i}} \rangle \otimes | \Psi_{\rm{i}}^{\rm{el}} \rangle \otimes |0 \rangle \ .
\end{equation}
%
Thereby, the initial electronic wave function is given by
%
\begin{equation}\label{eq:psi_i_el}
| \Psi_{\rm{i}}^{\rm{el}} \rangle = | \alpha_{\rm{i}} J_{\rm{i}} \mu_{\rm{i}}, \bm{p} m_{\rm{s}} \rangle\ ,
\end{equation}
%
where the electronic configuration $\alpha_{\rm{i}}$ and the total angular momentum $J_{\rm{i}}$ with projection $\mu_{\rm{i}}$ represent the initial state of the bound electrons. The free electron is characterized by its momentum $\bm{p}$ and spin projection quantum number $m_{\rm{s}}$. The nuclear ground state is determined by the total angular momentum $I_{\rm{i}}$ and its projection $M_{\rm{i}}$.

The resonant or intermediate state produced via NEEC is composed of the excited nucleus, the electronic capture state and the radiation field still in vacuum as illustrated in Fig.~\ref{fig:neec-process}. The direct product is given by
%
\begin{equation}\label{eq:dstate}
| \Psi_{\rm{d}} \rangle = | I_{\rm{d}}M_{\rm{d}}, \Psi_{\rm{d}}^{\rm{el}} ,0 \rangle \equiv 
| I_{\rm{d}}M_{\rm{d}} \rangle \otimes | \Psi_{\rm{d}}^{\rm{el}} \rangle \otimes |0 \rangle \ ,
\end{equation}
%
where the quantum numbers $I_{\rm{d}}$ and $M_{\rm{d}}$ determine the nuclear excited state. Since the free electron is captured into a bound level during the process of NEEC, the electronic state can be written as
%
\begin{equation}\label{eq:dstate_el}
| \Psi_{\rm{d}}^{\rm{el}} \rangle = | \alpha_{\rm{d}} J_{\rm{d}} \mu_{\rm{d}} \rangle
\end{equation}
%
with $\alpha_{\rm{d}}$ representing the electronic configuration, $J_{\rm{d}}$ the total angular momentum and $\mu_{\rm{d}}$ the projection quantum number of the NEEC capture level.

In the second step shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:neec-process}, the nuclear excited state decays back to the ground state by emitting a photon. The electronic state remains unchanged. Therefore, the final state is given by
%
\begin{equation}
| \Psi_{\rm{f}} \rangle = | I_{\rm{f}}M_{\rm{f}} , \Psi_{\rm{d}}^{\rm{el}} , \lambda kLM \rangle \equiv 
| I_{\rm{f}}M_{\rm{f}}\rangle \otimes | \Psi_{\rm{d}}^{\rm{el}} \rangle \otimes |\lambda k LM \rangle \ .
\label{psi_f}
\end{equation}
%
Again, the quantum numbers $I_{\rm{f}}$ and $M_{\rm{f}}$ describe the nucleus in the final state. Moreover, the nuclear radiative decay creates a photon with wave number $k$, total angular momentum $L$ and projection $M$. The parameter $\lambda$ determines whether an electric ($\lambda=\mathcal{E}$) or magnetic ($\lambda=\mathcal{M}$) wave is produced. This production process can be expressed in terms of the photon creation operator applied to the vacuum state,
%
\begin{equation}
|\lambda kLM\rangle=a^{\dagger}_{\lambda kLM}|0\rangle\ .
\end{equation}
%
The corresponding annihilation operator is denoted by $a_{\lambda kLM}$.


%\begin{equation}
%| \Psi_{\rm{f}}^{\rm{el}} \rangle = | \Psi_{\rm{d}}^{\rm{el}} \rangle
%\label{psi_{\rm{f}}_el}
%\end{equation}





%------------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\section{The system's Hamiltonian}
\label{sec:Hamiltonian}

The total Hamilton operator of the considered system is composed of nuclear, electronic and photonic degrees of freedom,
%
\begin{equation}\label{eq:totalH}
H = H_{\rm{n}} + H_{\rm{e}} + H_{\rm{r}} + H_{\rm{en}} + H_{\rm{er}} + H_{\rm{nr}} \ .
\end{equation}
%
Within our framework, the nucleus is described by a collective model. The main purpose of using this kind of model is to relate the nuclear matrix elements with available experimental data in order to stay independent of any nuclear wave function constructions (see Sec.~\ref{sec:nucl-model}). For the case of an even-even nucleus (even number of protons and even number of neutrons) the free nuclear Hamiltonian can be written as \cite{thesis-Ada}
%
\begin{equation}\label{eq:nuclearh}
H_{\rm{n}}=\sum_{\ell m}\omega_{\ell}\left(\beta^{\dagger}_{\ell m}\beta_{\ell m}+\frac{1}{2}\right)\ ,
\end{equation}
%
where $\beta^{\dagger}_{\ell m}$ and $\beta_{\ell m}$ are the phonon creation and annihilation operators of the collective modes with frequency $\omega_{\ell}$. 

The relativistic Dirac Hamiltonian is given by
%
\begin{equation}
H_{\rm{e}} = \sum_{i=1}^N \big[ c\bm{\alpha}\cdot\bm{p}_i+(\beta-1)c^2 \big] + \frac{1}{2} \sum_{i\neq j} \frac{1}{|\bm{r}_i-\bm{r}_j|}\ .
\label{eq:H_e}
\end{equation}
%
Here, $N$ is the number of electrons, $\bm{p}_i$ stands for the momentum of the $i^{\rm{th}}$ electron, $\bm{\alpha}$ denotes the vector composed of the Dirac matrices ($\alpha_x,\alpha_y,\alpha_z$) and $\beta$ represents the fourth Dirac matrix. Furthermore, the rest mass energy $c^2$ has been subtracted. Note that $H_{\rm{e}}$ also contains the electron-electron interactions which are given by the second summation in Eq.~\eqref{eq:H_e}. Here, the Breit interaction is not taken into account.

The Hamiltonian of the quantized radiation field is expressed in terms of the photon creation and annihilation operators with frequency $\omega_k$, namely
%
\begin{equation}
H_{\rm{r}} = \sum_{\lambda kLM} \omega_k a^{\dagger}_{\lambda kLM} a_{\lambda kLM}\ .
\end{equation}
%

The remaining Hamiltonians describe the interactions between the subspaces: $H_{\rm{en}}$ -- electron-nucleus interaction, $H_{\rm{er}}$ -- electron-radiation interaction and $H_{\rm{nr}}$ -- nucleus-radiation interaction. For the electron-nucleus interaction we apply the Coulomb gauge which renders it possible to split up the dominant Coulomb interaction,
%
\begin{equation}\label{eq:coulomb}
H_{\rm{en}} = \sum_{i=1}^N h_{\rm{en}}(i) = \sum_{i=1}^N \int \d^3r_{\rm{n}}\, \frac{\rho_{\rm{n}}(\bm{r}_{\rm{n}})}{|\bm{r}_i-\bm{r}_{\rm{n}}|} \ .
\end{equation} 
%
Thereby, $\bm{r}_{\rm{n}}$ and $\bm{r}_i$ stand for the spatial coordinates of the nucleus and the $i^{\rm{th}}$ electron, respectively. The nuclear charge density is represented by $\rho_{\rm{n}}$. The Coulomb-type Hamiltonian $H_{\rm{en}}$ describes the electric interaction between the electron and the nucleus and will be responsible for electric NEEC transitions.

By using the multipole expansion of the electromagnetic vector potential the interaction between the electron and the quantized radiation field can be written as
%
\begin{equation}\label{eq:radhamilton}
H_{\rm{er}} = -\sum_{i=1}^N \bm{\alpha}\cdot\bm{A}(\bm{r}_i) = \sum_{i=1}^N \sum_{\lambda k LM} \left(a^{\dagger}_{\lambda kLM}\bm{\alpha}\cdot\bm{A}_{\lambda k LM}(\bm{r}_i)+{\rm H.c.} \right)\ ,
\end{equation}
%
where $\bm{A}_{\lambda k LM}$ with $\lambda=\mathcal{E}$ and $\lambda=\mathcal{M}$ represent the electric and magnetic multipole fields, respectively. Both are eigenfunctions of $\bm{L}^2$ and $L_z$ and fulfill the field-free Maxwell equations. Taking a spherical quantization volume of radius $R$ they are given by \cite{RingSchuck}
%
\begin{align}
\bm{A}_{(\mathcal{M})kLM}(\bm{r})&=\sqrt{\frac{4\pi ck}{R}}j_L(kr)\bm{Y}^M_{LL}(\theta,\varphi)\ ,
\nonumber \\ \label{eq:multipole-fields-qu}
\bm{A}_{(\mathcal{E})kLM}(\bm{r})&=\frac{\i}{k}\sqrt{\frac{4\pi ck}{R}}\nabla\times\bigg(j_L(kr)\bm{Y}^M_{LL}(\theta,\varphi)\bigg)\ ,
\end{align}
%
closely related to the semiclassical case [see Eq.~\eqref{eq:multipole-fields}] where the normalization due to a finite quantization volume was not required. The term $j_L$ represents the spherical Bessel function and $\bm{Y}^M_{JL}$ stands for the vector spherical harmonics defined in Eq.~\eqref{vsh}.
%by
%%
%\begin{equation}
%\bm{Y}^M_{JL}(\theta,\varphi)=\sum_\nu\sum_q C\big(L\ 1\ J;\nu\ q\ M\big)Y_{L\nu}(\theta,\varphi)\bm{\varepsilon}_q\ .
%\label{vsh}
%\end{equation}
%%
%The spherical unit vectors $\bm{\varepsilon}_q$ ($q=0,\pm1$) can be expressed in terms of the Cartesian unit vectors as follows
%\begin{align}
%\label{eq:NFS_n0}
%\bm{\varepsilon}_0 &= \bm{e}_z\ , \\
%\label{eq:NFS_n+-1}
%\bm{\varepsilon}_{\pm1} &= \mp \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \left( \bm{e}_x \pm \i\bm{e}_y \right)\ .
%\end{align}
%%
%The vector spherical harmonics are irreducible tensors of rank $J$ with components $M=-J,\dots,J$. Thereby, $J$ is subject to $L-1 \le J \le L+1$ due to the Clebsch Gordan coefficient $C(L\ 1\ J;\nu\ q\ M)$. 

By making use of the multipole expansion of the electromagnetic field, $H_{\rm{nr}}$ can be analogously expressed in terms of the electric and magnetic multipole fields,
%
\begin{equation}
\label{H_nr}
H_{\rm{nr}} = -\frac{1}{c}\sum_{\lambda k LM} \left(a^{\dagger}_{\lambda k LM}\int \d^3r_{\rm{n}}\, \bm{j}_{\rm{n}}(\bm{r}_{\rm{n}})\cdot\bm{A}_{\lambda k LM}(\bm{r}_{\rm{n}}) + {\rm H.c.} \right)\ ,
\end{equation}
%
where $\bm{j}_{\rm{n}}$ is the nuclear current density. Likewise in Eq.~\eqref{eq:coulomb}, the integration is performed over the complete nuclear volume. Note that according to the chosen normalization in Eq.~\eqref{eq:multipole-fields-qu} we obtain the following commutation relations for the photon creation and annihilation operators \cite{RingSchuck}
%
\begin{align}
[ a_{\lambda k LM},a_{\lambda' k' L'M'} ] &= 0, \nonumber \\ \label{commutation}
[ a_{\lambda k LM},a^{\dagger}_{\lambda' k' L'M'} ] &= \delta_{\lambda \lambda'} \delta_{k k'} \delta_{L L'} \delta_{M M'}\ .
\end{align}


%------------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\subsection{Magnetic interaction}
\label{sec:magn-H}

The total Hamiltonian presented in Eq.~\eqref{eq:totalH} can be split into an unperturbed part $H_0$ and an interaction part $V$ by making use of the Feshbach projection operator method. For instance, the interaction part $V$ can be written as a sum whose terms exactly describe transitions between the subspaces defined in Sec.~\ref{sec:decomposition}. Applying further an infinite perturbation expansion to the transition operator $T$ known from scattering theory, it is possible to include energy corrections due to Coulomb nuclear polarization, nuclear self-energy and electronic one-loop self energy \cite{thesis-Ada}. Moreover, transition widths caused by radiative decay or internal conversion are introduced. In many electron systems it is also possible to account for Breit interactions between the electronic currents in this way \cite{thesis-Ada}.

Apart of these energy corrections, in the second-order term one can identify the Hamiltonian responsible for the magnetic interaction between the electronic and nuclear currents. According to Ref.~\cite{thesis-Ada}, the magnetic Hamiltonian reads
%
\begin{equation}
H_{\rm{magn}} = \sum_{i=1}^N \mathcalboondox{h}_{\rm{magn}}(i) = - \sum_{i=1}^N \frac{1}{c} \bm{\alpha}\cdot \int \d^3r_{\rm{n}}\, \frac{\bm{j}_{\rm{n}}(\bm{r}_{\rm{n}})}{|\bm{r}_i-\bm{r}_{\rm{n}}|}  \ .
\label{hmagn}
\end{equation}
%
This term describes the magnetic interaction between the electron and the nucleus by the exchange of a transverse photon. In other words, electrons interact with the vector potential produced by the nuclear current. For us, $H_{\rm{magn}}$ is specifically important for the magnetic NEEC transitions discussed in Sec.~\ref{sec:Y-NEEC}.


%------------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\subsection{Nuclear model}
\label{sec:nucl-model}

We describe the nucleus by using a collective model whose underlying physical picture is that of a classical charged liquid drop \cite{RingSchuck, BlattWeisskopf}. In this model the interior structure, i.e., the composition of the nucleus by individual nucleons is totally neglected. The nucleus is considered as a liquid drop with a sharp surface which is filled with homogeneous nuclear matter with constant density. This kind of description is only applicable if the size of the individual nucleons is much smaller than the total size of the nucleus. Hence, the validity of the collective model increases with the weight of considered nuclei. Excitations of the nucleus can be described in this framework as vibrations and rotations of the nuclear surface.

Using the collective model it can be shown that the nuclear charge density $\rho_{\rm{n}}$ can be split up into two terms, a static one which describes the nuclear ground state and a term responsible for nuclear excitations. Following Ref.~\cite{thesis-Ada}, these are given by
%
\begin{align}
\rho_{\rm{n}} ^{\rm{st}}(\bm{r}) &= \rho_0 \Theta( R_0 - r )\ , \nonumber \\
\rho_{\rm{n}} ^{\rm{exc}}(\bm{r}) &= \rho_0 \delta(R_0 - r) R_0 \sum_{\ell m} \alpha_{\ell m}^* Y_{\ell m}(\theta,\varphi)\ ,
\end{align}
%
where $R_0$ represents the radius of the liquid drop and the time-dependent amplitudes $\alpha_{\ell m}^*$ describe fluctuations of the nuclear surface. The parameter $\rho_0$ is given by $\frac{3 Z}{4 \pi R_0^3}$. Inserting the explicit form of $\rho_{\rm{n}}$ into Eq.~\eqref{eq:coulomb}, the interaction Hamiltonian $h_{\rm{en}}$ splits up in the same manner into a static part $\mathcalboondox{h}^{\rm{st}}_{\rm{en}}$ and a dynamical part $\mathcalboondox{h}_{\rm{en}}$ which is responsible for the electron-nucleus interaction describing excitations of electric type. For $r_{\rm{e}} > r_{\rm{n}}$ the static part evaluates to the well-known spherical Coulomb potential $V_C = -\frac{Z}{|\bm{r}_{\rm{e}}-\bm{r}_{\rm{n}}|}$. Since we are dealing with single-particle Hamiltonians we drop the particle index $i$ and replace $\bm{r}_i$ by $\bm{r}_{\rm{e}}$ in order to clearly differentiate between nuclear and electronic coordinates. Whenever using the single-particle Hamiltonians $\mathcalboondox{h}_{\rm{en}}$ or $\mathcalboondox{h}_{\rm{magn}}$ in the following these replacement rules apply.

The collective model is specifically important for our theoretical treatment of NEEC because it allows to relate the electric and magnetic interaction Hamiltonians with the nuclear multipole moments. Following the procedure presented Chap.~2 of Ref.~\cite{thesis-Ada}, the following expressions can be obtained for $\mathcalboondox{h}_{\rm{en}}$ and $\mathcalboondox{h}_{\rm{magn}}$,
%
\begin{align}
\mathcalboondox{h}_{\rm{en}}&=\sum_{LM}\frac{\mathcalboondox{Q}_{LM}}{R_0^{L}}\int \d^3r_{\rm{n}} \, \frac{\delta(R_0-r_{\rm{n}})
Y_{LM}^*(\theta_{\rm{n}},\varphi_{\rm{n}})}{|\bm{r}_{\rm{e}}-\bm{r}_{\rm{n}}|}\ ,\nonumber \\
\mathcalboondox{h}_{\rm{magn}}&=-\i\sum_{LM}\frac{4\pi}{2L+1}\sqrt{\frac{L+1}{L}}
r_{\rm{e}}^{-(L+1)}\mathcalboondox{M}_{LM}\bm{\alpha}\cdot\bm{Y}^{M*}_{LL}(\theta_{\rm{e}},\varphi_{\rm{e}})\ ,
\label{H_en:work}
\end{align} 
%
where the electric and magnetic multipole moments $\mathcalboondox{Q}_{LM}$ and $\mathcalboondox{M}_{LM}$ are the ones defined in Eqs.~\eqref{eq:Q_LM} and \eqref{eq:M_LM}.
%by \cite{RingSchuck}
%
%\begin{eqnarray}
%\mathcalboondox{Q}_{LM}&=&\int d^3r \, r^{L} Y_{LM}(\theta,\varphi)\rho_{\rm{n}} ^{\rm{exc}}(\bm{r})\ ,\\
%\mathcalboondox{M}_{LM}&=&-\frac{\i}{c}\sqrt{\frac{L}{L+1}}\int d^3r \, r^{L}\bm{Y}^{M}_{LL}(\theta,\varphi)\cdot\bm{j}_{\rm{n}}(\bm{r})\ .
%\end{eqnarray}
%
Analogously to the previous Chapter, the matrix elements between the nuclear multipole moments can be expressed in terms of the reduced transition probabilities $\mathcal{B} (\mathcal{E}(\mathcal{M})L,I_{\rm{i}}\to  I_{\rm{d}})$ whose definitions can be found in Eqs.~\eqref{eq:B_el} and \eqref{eq:B_mag}.
%
%\be
%\mathcal{B} (\mathcal{E}(\mathcal{M})L,I_{\rm{i}}\to  I_{\rm{d}})=\frac{1}{2I_{\rm{i}}+1}\big|\langle  I_{\rm{d}}\|\mathcalboondox{Q}_{L}(\mathcalboondox{M}_{L})\|I_{\rm{i}}\rangle \big|^2\ .
%\ee
%
This means ultimately that the nuclear part of the NEEC transition amplitudes can be related to $\mathcal{B}$ values for which experimental data is available. 
We use experimental values for the reduced transition probabilities in order to evaluate the nuclear matrix elements as it was shown in the previous Chapter.



%------------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\section{Total NEEC cross section}
\label{sec:sigma-NEEC}


For the calculation of the NEEC cross section we assume that the projection quantum numbers of \ket{\Psi_{\rm{i}}} and \ket{\Psi_{\rm{d}}} are not resolved in the experiment. This is done by averaging over $M_{\rm{i}}$, $\mu_{\rm{i}}$ and $m_{\rm{s}}$ and summing over $M_{\rm{d}}$ and $\mu_{\rm{d}}$. Furthermore, we integrate over the solid angle $\Omega_{\bm{p}}$ of the incoming electrons. For the general case of both electric and/or magnetic transitions,  the NEEC cross section reads \cite{thesis-Ada, Adriana2006.PRA}
%
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{\rm{neec}}^{\rm{i} \to \rm{d}}(E)=\frac{2\pi}{F_{\rm{i}}} \frac{1}{2(2I_{\rm{i}}+1)(2J_{\rm{i}}+1)}\sum_{{M_{\rm{i}}} \mu_{\rm{i}} m_{\rm{s}}}\sum_{M_{\rm{d}} \mu_{\rm{d}}} \frac{1}{4\pi}
\int \d\Omega_{\bm{p}} \,
\frac{\big|\langle \Psi_{\rm{d}} |H_{\rm{N}}| \Psi_{\rm{i}} \rangle\big|^2\, \Gamma_{\rm{d}}/2\pi}{(E-E_{\rm{d}})^2 + \Gamma_{\rm{d}}^2/4 } \ ,
\label{eq:sigma_neec}
\end{equation}
%
where $F_{\rm{i}}$ stands for the incoming electron flux. Here, the isolated resonance approximation has been applied where only a single resonant state $\Psi_{\rm{d}}$ with resonance energy $E_{\rm{d}}$ and natural width $\Gamma_{\rm{d}}$ is taken into account. The interaction Hamiltonian $H_{\rm{N}}$ describes transitions of both electric and magnetic multipolarity induced by the electron-nucleus interaction and is defined by
%
\begin{equation}
H_{\rm{N}} = \sum_{i=1}^N \big[ \mathcalboondox{h}_{\rm{en}}(i) + \mathcalboondox{h}_{\rm{magn}}(i)  \big]\ .
\end{equation}
%
In order to write $\sigma_{\rm{neec}}^{\rm{i} \to \rm{d}}$ in a more compact form the NEEC rate $Y_{\rm{neec}}^{\rm{i} \to \rm{d}}$ is introduced,
%
\begin{equation}
Y_{\rm{neec}}^{\rm{i} \to \rm{d}}=\frac{2\pi}{2(2I_{\rm{i}}+1)(2J_{\rm{i}}+1)}\sum_{{M_{\rm{i}}} \mu_{\rm{i}} m_{\rm{s}}}\sum_{M_{\rm{d}} \mu_{\rm{d}}}
\int \d\Omega_{\bm{p}} \,
\big|\langle \Psi_{\rm{d}} |H_{\rm{N}}| \Psi_{\rm{i}} \rangle\big|^2 \rho_{\rm{i}}\ .
\label{eq:Yrate}
\end{equation}
%
Using that the incoming electron flux $F_{\rm{i}}$ and the initial density of continuum electron states $\rho_{\rm{i}}$ are related by $F_{\rm{i}} \rho_{\rm{i}} = \frac{p^2}{(2 \pi)^3}$, the NEEC cross section can be written in terms of $Y_{\rm{neec}}^{\rm{i} \to \rm{d}}$ as
%
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{\rm{neec}}^{\rm{i} \to \rm{d}}=\frac{2\pi^2}{p^2} Y_{\rm{neec}}^{\rm{i} \to \rm{d}} L_{\rm{d}}(E-E_{\rm{d}})\ ,
\label{eq:sigma_neec_compact}
\end{equation}
%
where $p$ is the absolute value of the free electron momentum $\bm{p}$. The function $L_{\rm{d}}$ represents the well-known normalized Lorentz profile occurring in resonant systems,
%
\begin{equation}
L_{\rm{d}}(E-E_{\rm{d}}) = \frac{\Gamma_{\rm{d}} / 2\pi}{(E-E_{\rm{d}})^2 + \Gamma_{\rm{d}}^2/4}\ .
\label{lorentz}
\end{equation}
%
For arbitrary capture levels $\Psi_{\rm{d}}$ the width $\Gamma_{\rm{d}}$ is composed of an electronic and a nuclear part, $\Gamma_{\rm{d}} = \Gamma_{\rm{d}}^{\rm{el}} + \Gamma_{\rm{d}}^{\rm{nucl}}$. The nuclear width itself can be split into a radiative term and a contribution via IC,
%
\begin{equation}
\Gamma_{\rm{d}}^{\rm{nucl}} = \sum_{\rm{f'}} \big( A_{\rm{r}}^{\rm{d} \to \rm{f'}} + A_{\rm{ic}}^{\rm{d} \to \rm{f'}}\big)\ ,
\end{equation}
%
where the index $\rm{f'}$ stands for an arbitrary final state $\Psi_{\rm{f'}}$. In the case of IC this state can generally be written as 
%
\begin{equation}
\ketm{\Psi_{\rm{f'}}} = \ketm{ I_{\rm{f'}} M_{\rm{f'}}, (\alpha_{\rm{f'}} J_{\rm{f'}} \mu_{\rm{f'}}, \mathbf{p}' m_{\rm{s}}'), 0}\ ,
\end{equation}
%
where the state notation exactly follows that of Sec.~\ref{sec:decomposition}. The IC transition rate $A_{\rm{ic}}^{\rm{d} \to \rm{f'}}$ can be related to $Y_{\rm{neec}}^{\rm{f'} \to \rm{d}}$ using the principle of detailed balance,
%
\begin{equation}
A_{\rm{ic}}^{\rm{d} \to \rm{f'}} = \frac{2(2I_{\rm{f'}}+1)(2J_{\rm{f'}}+1)}{(2I_{\rm{d}}+1)(2J_{\rm{d}}+1)} Y_{\rm{neec}}^{\rm{f'} \to \rm{d}}\ .
\end{equation}
%
Consequently, IC rates are highly dependent on the electronic structure of the considered atom and can be hence modified by removing or adding electrons from or to the atomic shells. A bare nucleus, for instance, can only decay radiatively. Moreover, it is important to note that IC can only take place if the nuclear excitation energy is above the ionization threshold of the bound electrons present.

In contrast, the radiative decay rate $A_{\rm{r}}^{\rm{d} \to \rm{f'}}$ is independent of the electronic structure. $A_{\rm{r}}^{\rm{d} \to \rm{f'}}$ is completely determined by the nuclear matrix elements of $H_{\rm{nr}}$. The nuclear radiative decay of $\Psi_{\rm{d}}$ leads in general to a final state which has the form of $\Psi_{\rm{f}}$ defined in Eq.~\eqref{psi_f}. The corresponding decay rate $A_{\rm{r}}^{\rm{d} \to \rm{f}}$ can be expressed as
%
\begin{equation}
A_{\rm{r}}^{\rm{d} \to \rm{f}} = \frac{2\pi}{2I_{\rm{d}} + 1} \sum_{M_{\rm{f}} M} \sum_{M_{\rm{d}}}
\big|\langle \Psi_{\rm{f}} | H_{\rm{nr}} | \Psi_{\rm{d}} \rangle \big|^2\rho_{\rm{f}}  \ .
\label{Rrate}
\end{equation}
%
Following the procedure in Ref.~\cite{RingSchuck}, the matrix elements of $H_{\rm{nr}}$ can be connected to the reduced transition probabilities $\mathcal{B}$ leading to the expression of $A_{\rm{r}}$ already given in Eq.~\eqref{eq:A_r}.

Typically, the nuclear width takes values between $10^{-5}$ and $10^{-10}$ eV which makes it often very hard to fulfill the nuclear resonance condition. However, the peak value on resonance $E=E_{\rm{d}}$ can be very large. Therefore, it is often more reasonable to speak about the integrated cross section, the so-called resonance strength.
%
%\begin{equation}
%S_{\rm{neec}}^{\rm{i} \to \rm{d}}=\int dE\ \frac{2\pi^2}{p^2}
%Y_{\rm{neec}}^{\rm{i} \to \rm{d}} L_{\rm{d}}(E-E_{\rm{d}}) \ .
%\end{equation}
%
Integrating Eq.~(\ref{eq:sigma_neec_compact}) over the continuum energy $E$ and considering $p^2$ and $Y_{\rm{neec}}^{\rm{i} \to \rm{d}}$ constant over the region $\Gamma_{\rm{d}}$ leads to the following resonance strength expression for NEEC
%
\begin{equation}
S_{\rm{neec}}^{\rm{i} \to \rm{d}}=\frac{2\pi^2}{p^2}
Y_{\rm{neec}}^{\rm{i} \to \rm{d}}  \ .
\end{equation}
%
Here, it was used that the integral of the Lorentz function $L_{\rm{d}}$ is normalized to unity.

So far we only discussed the population of the nuclear excited state via NEEC. In order to incorporate the second step, the nuclear decay, the so-called branching ratio can be employed \cite{BlattWeisskopf}. In general, the two-step cross section for NEEC followed by the nuclear decay can be written as
%
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{\rm{neec}}^{\rm{i} \to \rm{d} \to \rm{f}}=\sigma_{\rm{neec}}^{\rm{i} \to \rm{d}} B^{\rm{d} \to \rm{f}}\ ,
\label{eq:sigma_2step}
\end{equation}
%
where the branching ratio $B^{\rm{d} \to \rm{f}}$ describes the probability of the considered decay channel. For instance, in the case of NEEC followed by radiative decay as illustrated in Fig.~\ref{fig:neec-process}, $B^{\rm{d} \to \rm{f}}$ evaluates to
%
\begin{equation}
B^{\rm{d} \to \rm{f}} = \frac{A_{\rm{r}}^{\rm{d} \to \rm{f}}}{\Gamma_{\rm{d}}^{\rm{nucl}}}\ .
\label{eq:branching-ratio}
\end{equation}
%
Since we are later on only interested in the relative probability of a certain nuclear decay channel, the nuclear part $\Gamma_{\rm{d}}^{\rm{nucl}}$ has been used in Eq.~\eqref{eq:branching-ratio} instead of the full width $\Gamma_{\rm{d}}$ which may also have electronic contributions.





%------------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\section{Excitation rate via NEEC}
\label{sec:Y-NEEC}



For the calculation of the NEEC rate $Y_{\rm{neec}}^{\rm{i} \to \rm{d}}$ given in Eq.~\eqref{eq:Yrate} it is helpful to first reduce the many-electron matrix elements to matrix elements of the ``active'' electron only (the electron which undergoes the capture process) by employing the single-active electron approximation \cite{Agrigapudi2012.PRA}. Therefore, we use the theory of angular momentum coupling \cite{Edmonds} in order to compose the electronic capture level $| \alpha_{\rm{d}} J_{\rm{d}} \mu_{\rm{d}} \rangle$ into a many-electron part determined by $\alpha_{\rm{i}}$, $J_{\rm{i}}$ and $\mu_{\rm{i}}$ and an active-electron part characterized by the set of quantum numbers $n_{\rm{d}}$, $\kappa_{\rm{d}}$ and $m_{\rm{d}}$, 
%
\begin{equation}\label{eq:dstate_el-1}
| \Psi_{\rm{d}}^{\rm{el}} \rangle = | \alpha_{\rm{d}} J_{\rm{d}} \mu_{\rm{d}} \rangle = \sum_{\mu_{\rm{i}} m_{\rm{d}}} C\big(J_{\rm{i}}\ j_{\rm{d}}\ J_{\rm{d}};\mu_{\rm{i}}\ m_{\rm{d}}\ \mu_{\rm{d}}\big) |\alpha_{\rm{i}} J_{\rm{i}} \mu_{\rm{i}}, n_{\rm{d}} \kappa_{\rm{d}} m_{\rm{d}} \rangle \ .
\end{equation}
%
The coupling weights of the superposition are given by the Clebsch-Gordan coefficients $C(J_{\rm{i}}\ j_{\rm{d}}\ J_{\rm{d}};\mu_{\rm{i}}\ m_{\rm{d}}\ \mu_{\rm{d}})$. The total and orbital angular momentum of $|n_{\rm{d}} \kappa_{\rm{d}} m_{\rm{d}}\rangle$ are denoted as $j_{\rm{d}} = |\kappa_{\rm{d}}|-\frac{1}{2}$ and $l_{\rm{d}}$, respectively. Furthermore, it is possible to write the interaction Hamiltonian $H_{\rm{N}}$ occurring in Eq.~\eqref{eq:Yrate} as a direct product of a part only acting on the nuclear degrees of freedom and an electronic part, $H_{\rm{N}} = H_{\rm{N}}^{\rm{nucl}} \otimes H_{\rm{N}}^{\rm{el}}$. The matrix elements of $H_{\rm{N}}^{\rm{el}}$ evaluate in our case to
%
\begin{align}
\langle \Psi_{\rm{d}}^{\rm{el}} | H_{\rm{N}}^{\rm{el}} |  \Psi_{\rm{i}}^{\rm{el}} \rangle &= \sum_{\mu_{\rm{i}}' m_{\rm{d}}} C\big(J_{\rm{i}}\ j_{\rm{d}}\ J_{\rm{d}};\mu_{\rm{i}}'\ m_{\rm{d}}\ \mu_{\rm{d}}\big) \langle \alpha_{\rm{i}} J_{\rm{i}} \mu_{\rm{i}}', n_{\rm{d}} \kappa_{\rm{d}} m_{\rm{d}} | H_{\rm{N}}^{\rm{el}} |  \alpha_{\rm{i}} J_{\rm{i}} \mu_{\rm{i}}, \bm{p} m_{\rm{s}} \rangle \nonumber \\
&= \sum_{m_{\rm{d}}} C\big(J_{\rm{i}}\ j_{\rm{d}}\ J_{\rm{d}};\mu_{\rm{i}}\ m_{\rm{d}}\ \mu_{\rm{d}}\big) \langle n_{\rm{d}} \kappa_{\rm{d}} m_{\rm{d}} | \mathcalboondox{h}_{\rm{N}}^{\rm{el}} |  \bm{p} m_{\rm{s}} \rangle \ .
\label{eq:many-single}
\end{align}
%
Here, the single-active electron approximation \cite{Agrigapudi2012.PRA} was applied in order to derive the second line of Eq.~\eqref{eq:many-single} where we assume that the initial bound electronic wave function does not change by adding an additional electron.

The further calculation of the single-electron matrix elements requires the continuum electron states with definite asymptotic momentum $\bm{p}$ and spin projection $m_{\rm{s}}$ to be expanded in terms of partial waves $| \varepsilon\kappa m\rangle$ \cite{Eichler-report},
%
\begin{equation}
|\bm{p} m_{\rm{s}}\rangle=\sum_{\kappa m}\i^l \e^{\i\Delta_{\kappa}}\sum_{m_l}Y_{l m_l}^*(\theta_{\bm{p}},\varphi_{\bm{p}})
C\big(l\ \frac{1}{2}\ j;m_l\ m_{\rm{s}} \ m\big)| \varepsilon\kappa m\rangle\ ,
\label{eq:pwe}
\end{equation}
%
where $\varepsilon$ represents the kinetic energy, $\varepsilon=\sqrt{p^2c^2+c^4}-c^2$ and $\kappa$ the eigenvalue of the relativistic spin-orbit operator (analogously to $\kappa_{\rm{d}}$). The total and orbital angular momentum of the partial wave are defined as $j$ and $l$. $\Delta_{\kappa}$ is the so-called Coulomb phase which ensures the correct boundary conditions. In the case of electron capture, the electronic boundary condition consists of an incoming plane wave and an outgoing spherical wave. The further derivation of the NEEC transition rates is divided into the special cases of electric and magnetic multipolarity.





%------------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\subsection{Electric transitions}

By considering NEEC transitions of electric multipolarity and using Eq.~\eqref{eq:many-single}, Eq.~\eqref{eq:Yrate} simplifies to
%
\begin{align}
Y_{\rm{neec}}^{\rm{i} \to \rm{d}} &= \frac{2\pi (2J_{\rm{d}}+1)}{2(2I_{\rm{i}}+1)(2J_{\rm{i}}+1)(2j_{\rm{d}}+1)}
 \nonumber \\
&\qquad \times 
\sum_{M_{\rm{i}} m_{\rm{s}}}\sum_{M_{\rm{d}}  m_{\rm{d}}}
\int d\Omega_{\bm{p}} \,
\big|\langle I_{\rm{d}}M_{\rm{d}}, n_{\rm{d}} \kappa_{\rm{d}} m_{\rm{d}} ,0 |\mathcalboondox{h}_{\rm{en}}| I_{\rm{i}}M_{\rm{i}}, \bm{p} m_{\rm{s}} ,0 \rangle\big|^2 \rho_{\rm{i}} \ ,
\label{eq:Yneec-el-0}
\end{align}
%
where only the Coulomb interaction $\mathcalboondox{h}_{\rm{en}}$ contributes. In order to calculate the occurring matrix element we make use of the multipole expansion \cite{Edmonds}
%
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{|\bm{r}_{\rm{e}}-\bm{r}_{\rm{n}}|}=\sum_{L=0}^{\infty}\sum_{M=-L}^L \frac{4\pi}{2L+1}Y_{LM}(\theta_{\rm{n}},\varphi_{\rm{n}})Y^*_{LM}(\theta_{\rm{e}},\varphi_{\rm{e}})\frac{r^L_{<}}{r^{L+1}_{>}}\ ,
\end{equation}
%
where the following notation has been introduced: $r_{<}=r_{\rm{n}}$ and $r_{>}=r_{\rm{e}}$ if $r_{\rm{n}}<r_{\rm{e}}$; $r_{<}=r_{\rm{e}}$ and $r_{>}=r_{\rm{n}}$ if $r_{\rm{n}}>r_{\rm{e}}$. Inserting the multipole expansion into the definition of $\mathcalboondox{h}_{\rm{en}}$ [Eqs.~\eqref{H_en:work}] and integrating over the angular coordinates leads us to the following expression
%
\begin{align}
\langle \Psi_{\rm{d}} |\mathcalboondox{h}_{\rm{en}}| \Psi_{\rm{i}}\rangle&= \sum_{LM} \frac{1}{R_0^{L+2}}\, \frac{4\pi}{2L+1}\langle I_{\rm{d}}M_{\rm{d}}|\mathcalboondox{Q}_{LM}|I_{\rm{i}}M_{\rm{i}}\rangle
\nonumber \\ 
&\qquad
\times \langle n_{\rm{d}}\kappa_{\rm{d}}m_{\rm{d}}|Y^*_{LM}(\theta_{\rm{e}},\varphi_{\rm{e}})\int_0^{\infty} \d r_{\rm{n}}\, r_{\rm{n}}^2\frac{r^L_{<}}{r^{L+1}_{>}}\delta(R_0-r_{\rm{n}})|\bm{p}m_{\rm{s}}\rangle\ .
\label{elme1}
\end{align}
%
Since the multipole operator $\mathcalboondox{Q}_{LM}$ is a spherical tensor, the nuclear matrix element occurring in Eq.~\eqref{elme1} can be related to the reduced transition probabilities by applying the Wigner-Eckart theorem [analogously to Eq.~\eqref{eq:me-B_el}].
%
%\begin{eqnarray}
%\langle I_{\rm{d}}M_{\rm{d}}|\mathcalboondox{Q}_{LM}|I_{\rm{i}}M_{\rm{i}}\rangle&=&\frac{(-1)^{I_{\rm{i}}-M_{\rm{i}}}}{\sqrt{2L+1}}C\big(I_{\rm{d}}\ I_{\rm{i}}\ L;M_{\rm{d}}\ -M_{\rm{i}}\ M\big) \langle I_{\rm{d}}\|\mathcalboondox{Q}_{L}\|I_{\rm{i}}\rangle \nonumber \\
%&=& (-1)^{I_{\rm{i}}-M_{\rm{i}}} \sqrt{\frac{2I_{\rm{i}}+1}{2L+1}}C\big(I_{\rm{d}}\ I_{\rm{i}}\ L;M_{\rm{d}}\ -M_{\rm{i}}\ M\big)
%\nonumber \\ &&\times \mathcal{B}(\mathcal{E}L,I_{\rm{i}} \to I_{\rm{d}})\ .
%\end{eqnarray}
%
%From the first to the second line, the definition of the reduced transition probabilities given in Eq.~\eqref{} was used.

The calculation of the electronic matrix element appearing in Eq.~\eqref{elme1} is shown in App.~\ref{app:NEEC}. Putting everything together and by making use of some Clebsch-Gordan algebra, we finally obtain
%
\begin{equation}
{Y^{(\mathcal{E}L)}_{\rm{neec}}}=\frac{4\pi^2\rho_{\rm{i}}}{(2L+1)^2}R_0^{-2(L+2)} \mathcal{B}(\mathcal{E}L,I_{\rm{i}}\to I_{\rm{d}}) \frac{2J_{\rm{d}}+1}{2J_{\rm{i}}+1}
\sum_\kappa
C\big(j_{\rm{d}}\ L\ j;\frac{1}{2}\ 0\ \frac{1}{2}\big)^2 \left|R^{(\mathcal{E})}_{L,\kappa_{\rm{d}},\kappa}\right|^2\ .
\label{eq:Yneec_el}
\end{equation}
%
The occurring radial integral $R^{(\mathcal{E})}_{L,\kappa_{\rm{d}},\kappa}$ has to be evaluated numerically and is defined by
%
\begin{align}
R^{(\mathcal{E})}_{L,\kappa_{\rm{d}},\kappa}&=\frac{1}{R_0^{L-1}}\int_0^{R_0} \d r_{\rm{e}}\, r_{\rm{e}}^{L+2}\bigg(f_{n_{\rm{d}}\kappa_{\rm{d}}}(r_{\rm{e}})f_{\varepsilon\kappa}(r_{\rm{e}})+
g_{n_{\rm{d}}\kappa_{\rm{d}}}(r_{\rm{e}})g_{\varepsilon\kappa}(r_{\rm{e}})\bigg) \nonumber \\
&\qquad
+R_0^{L+2}\int_{R_0}^\infty \d r_{\rm{e}}\, r_{\rm{e}}^{-L+1}\bigg(f_{n_{\rm{d}}\kappa_{\rm{d}}}(r_{\rm{e}})f_{\varepsilon\kappa}(r_{\rm{e}})+g_{n_{\rm{d}}\kappa_{\rm{d}}}(r_{\rm{e}})g_{\varepsilon\kappa}(r_{\rm{e}})\bigg)\ ,
\label{rrs}
\end{align}
%
with the relativistic continuum wave function
%
\begin{equation}
\Psi_{\varepsilon\kappa m}(\bm{r})=\left(\begin{array}{c} g_{\varepsilon\kappa}(r)\Omega_{\kappa}^{m}(\theta,\varphi)\\ \i f_{\varepsilon\kappa}(r)\Omega_{-\kappa}^{m}(\theta,\varphi)\end{array}
\right)
\label{cont_wf}
\end{equation}
%
and the relativistic bound wave function
%
\begin{equation}
\Psi_{n_{\rm{d}}\kappa_{\rm{d}}m_{\rm{d}}}(\bm{r})=\left(\begin{array}{c} g_{n_{\rm{d}}\kappa_{\rm{d}}}(r)\Omega_{\kappa_{\rm{d}}}^{m_{\rm{d}}}(\theta,\varphi)\\ \i f_{n_{\rm{d}}\kappa_{\rm{d}}}(r)\Omega_{-\kappa_{\rm{d}}}^{m_{\rm{d}}}(\theta,\varphi)\end{array}
\right)\ .
\label{bound_wf}
\end{equation}
%
Here, $g_{\varepsilon\kappa}$ and $f_{\varepsilon\kappa}$ denote the large and small radial components of the continuum Dirac spinor, $g_{n_{\rm{d}} \kappa_{\rm{d}}}$ and $f_{n_{\rm{d}} \kappa_{\rm{d}}}$ the corresponding quantities for the bound spinor and $\Omega_{\kappa}^{m}$ are the so-called spin-angular functions, respectively.



%------------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\subsection{Magnetic transitions}

In the case of magnetic transitions the NEEC rate is given by Eq.~\eqref{eq:Yneec-el-0} with the Coulomb interaction $\mathcalboondox{h}_{\rm{en}}$ being replaced by the magnetic Hamiltonian $\mathcalboondox{h}_{\rm{magn}}$. The occurring matrix element \me{\Psi_{\rm{d}}}{\mathcalboondox{h}_{\rm{magn}}}{\Psi_{\rm{i}}} is explicitly given by
%
\begin{align}
\langle \Psi_{\rm{d}} |\mathcalboondox{h}_{\rm{magn}}| \Psi_{\rm{i}}\rangle&=
 4\pi \i\sum_{LM}(-1)^M\sqrt{\frac{L+1}{L}}\frac{1}{2L+1}
\nonumber \\
&\qquad
\times
\langle  I_{\rm{d}} M_{\rm{d}}|\mathcalboondox{M}_{LM}|I_{\rm{i}} M_{\rm{i}}\rangle 
\langle n_{\rm{d}}\kappa_{\rm{d}} m_{\rm{d}}|r_{\rm{e}}^{-(L+1)}\bm{\alpha}\cdot\bm{Y}^{-M}_{LL}(\theta_{\rm{e}},\varphi_{\rm{e}})|\bm{p}m_{\rm{s}}\rangle
\ ,
\label{eq:aA1}
\end{align}
%
where the following relation was used
%
\be
\bm{Y}^{M*}_{JL}=(-1)^{L+J+M+1}\, \bm{Y}^{-M}_{JL}\ .
\ee
%
Analogously to electric transitions, the nuclear part can be again expressed in terms of the reduced transition probabilities $\mathcal{B}$, see Eq.~\eqref{eq:me-B_mag}.
%
%\begin{eqnarray}
%\langle I_{\rm{d}}M_{\rm{d}}|\mathcalboondox{M}_{LM}|I_{\rm{i}}M_{\rm{i}}\rangle&=& (-1)^{I_{\rm{i}}-M_{\rm{i}}} \sqrt{\frac{2I_{\rm{i}}+1}{2L+1}}C\big(I_{\rm{d}}\ I_{\rm{i}}\ L;M_{\rm{d}}\ -M_{\rm{i}}\ M\big)
%\nonumber \\ &&\times \mathcal{B}(\mathcal{M}L,I_{\rm{i}} \to I_{\rm{d}})\ .
%\end{eqnarray}
%
The remaining task is to calculate the electronic free-bound transition amplitude. The derivation is presented in App.~\ref{app:NEEC}. By furthermore using the definition of the Wigner 3$j$-symbols in terms of Clebsch-Gordan coefficients \cite{Edmonds}
%
\be
C\big(j_1\ j_2\ j;m_1\ m_2\ m\big)=(-1)^{m+j_1-j_2}\sqrt{2j+1}\threejm{j_1}{j_2}{j}{m_1}{m_2}{-m}\ ,
\label{Wigner-3j}
\ee 
%
the final result for the magnetic NEEC transition rate with fixed multipolarity $L$ is obtained
%
\begin{align}
{Y_{\rm{neec}}^{(\mathcal{M}L)}}&=\frac{4\pi^2\rho_{\rm{i}}}{L^2(2L+1)^2} \mathcal{B}(\mathcal{M}L,I_{\rm{i}}\to  I_{\rm{d}})  
\nonumber \\
&\qquad
\times
\frac{2J_{\rm{d}}+1}{2J_{\rm{i}}+1}
\sum_{\kappa}(2j+1)(\kappa_{\rm{d}}+\kappa)^2
\threejm{j_{\rm{d}}}{j}{L}{\frac{1}{2}}{-\frac{1}{2}}{0}^2 \left|R^{(\mathcal{M})}_{L,\kappa_{\rm{d}},\kappa}\right|^2\ .
\label{eq:Yneec_mag}
\end{align}
%
The radial integral $R^{(\mathcal{M})}_{L,\kappa_{\rm{d}},\kappa}$ is defined by
%
\be
R^{(\mathcal{M})}_{L,\kappa_{\rm{d}},\kappa}=\int_0^{\infty} \d r_{\rm{e}}\, r_{\rm{e}}^{-L+1}\bigg(g_{n_{\rm{d}}\kappa_{\rm{d}}}(r_{\rm{e}})f_{\varepsilon\kappa}(r_{\rm{e}})+f_{n_{\rm{d}}\kappa_{\rm{d}}}(r_{\rm{e}})g_{\varepsilon\kappa}(r_{\rm{e}})\bigg)\ ,
\ee
%
and requires a numerical approach to be solved analogously to $R^{(\mathcal{E})}_{L,\kappa_{\rm{d}},\kappa}$ in Eq.~\eqref{rrs}.



%------------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
%\section{Radiative decay rate}
%\label{sec:A-rad}


